<div class="track"><img alt="" src="http://hits.theguardian.com/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.5/47389?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Apremier-league-squad-sheets-fulham-arsenal%3A1955364&ch=Football&c3=Guardian&c4=Premier+League+%28Football%29%2CFulham+%28Football%29%2CArsenal+FC+%28Football%29%2CFootball%2CSport&c5=Europa+League%2CPremier+League&c6=&c7=2013%2F08%2F23+05%3A05&c8=1955364&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=Squad+sheets+%28football%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Fulham+v+Arsenal%3A+Squad+sheets&c66=Sport&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FSport%2FFootball%2FPremier+League" width="1" height="1" /></div><p>The fresh sense of crisis surrounding Arsenal has been eased by their midweek win over Fenerbahce but there remains pressure on Arsène Wenger's side to win following their unexpected loss to Aston Villa. Fulham, who could hand a debut to Scott Parker, are not expected to triumph given they have won three of their previous 24 Premier League games against the visitors. <strong>Sophy Coombes-Roberts</strong></p><p><strong>Kick-off </strong>Saturday 12.45pm<strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Venue</strong> Craven Cottage</p><p><strong>Last season </strong>Fulham 0 Arsenal 1</p><p><strong>Live</strong> BT Sport 1 <strong>Referee </strong>H Webb</p><p><strong>This season</strong> <strong>G</strong>1, <strong>Y</strong>1, <strong>R</strong>0, 1.00 cards per game</p><p><strong>Odds</strong> <strong>H</strong> 5-2 <strong>A</strong> 11-10 <strong>D</strong> 12-5</p><h2><strong>Fulham</strong></h2><p><strong>Subs from</strong> Etheridge, Briggs, Sidwell, Senderos, Ruiz, Kacaniklic, Frei, Karagounis, Rodallega, Trotta, Dejagah, Bent, Amorebieta</p><p><strong>Doubtful</strong> None</p><p><strong>Injured</strong> Stekelenburg (shoulder, Sep), Richardson (hamstring, Sep)</p><p><strong>Suspended</strong> None</p><p><strong>Form guide</strong> WWLLLL</p><p><strong>Disciplinary record</strong> Y3 R0</p><p><strong>Leading scorer</strong> Kasami 1</p><h2><strong>Arsenal</strong></h2><p><strong>Subs from</strong> Fabianski, Martinez, Miyaichi, Monreal, Frimpong, Zelalem, Gnabry, Podolski, Sanogo, Akpom</p><p><strong>Doubtful</strong> Miyaichi (rib)</p><p><strong>Injured</strong> Arteta (thigh, Oct), Vermaelen (back, Oct), Oxlade-Chamberlain (knee, Nov), Diaby (knee, Mar)</p><p><strong>Suspended</strong> Koscielny (one match)</p><p><strong>Form guide</strong> LWWWDW</p><p><strong>Disciplinary record</strong> Y3 R1</p><p><strong>Leading scorer</strong> Giroud 1</p><div class="related" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"><ul><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/premierleague">Premier League</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/fulham">Fulham</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/arsenal">Arsenal</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class="terms"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com">theguardian.com</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/help/terms-of-service">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/help/feeds">More Feeds</a></div><p style="clear:both" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663870/s/305136d5/sc/12/mf.gif' border='0'/><br clear='all'/>
</li>
<li class="rss-item"><a class="rss-item" href="http://feeds.theguardian.com/c/34708/f/663870/s/305136d6/sc/13/l/0L0Stheguardian0N0Cfootball0Cdavid0Econn0Einside0Esport0Eblog0C20A130Caug0C230Calan0Epardew0Esignings0Enewcastle0Efrustration/story01.htm"  title="The appointment of Joe Kinnear and Wonga's sponsorship leave..." target="_blank">Alan Pardew wants signings as Newcastle fans put shirt on frustration | David Conn</a> <br />
<div class="track"><img alt="" src="http://hits.theguardian.com/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.5/18702?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aalan-pardew-signings-newcastle-frustration%3A1955262&ch=Football&c3=Guardian&c4=Newcastle+United+%28Football%29%2CMike+Ashley%2CAlan+Pardew%2CJoe+Kinnear%2CTransfer+window+%28football%29%2CFootball%2CSport%2CWonga+%28Business%29&c5=Unclassified%2CPremier+League&c6=David+Conn&c7=2013%2F08%2F23+04%3A59&c8=1955262&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Inside+sport+blog%2CSport+blog&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Alan+Pardew+wants+signings+as+Newcastle+fans+put+shirt+on+frustration&c66=Sport&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FSport%2FFootball%2FNewcastle+United" width="1" height="1" /></div><p class="standfirst">The appointment of Joe Kinnear and Wonga's sponsorship leave some supporters questioning the direction of their club</p><p>Newcastle United's renaissance at the inception of the Premier League was rallied by the club's then owner, Sir John Hall, as a flagship for an economic revival of the north east and the restored pride of the "Geordie nation". There was a hollowness in the rhetoric from a man whose fortune was made building a shopping mall, the Gateshead Metrocentre, on a former industrial site and Hall made £75m from selling his shares, ultimately to Mike Ashley, in 2007. So perhaps today's unhappy club, owned by another retail magnate and advertising Wonga payday loans to an economically depressed city, represents the fruition of Hall's vision rather than a&nbsp;shortfall.</p><p>At a downbeat press conference ahead of Saturday's home game against West Ham United at St James' Park, Alan Pardew spoke of Newcastle as financially vulnerable to bigger clubs in the transfer market and said he understood fans' "despondency". This with August sunshine still warming the training pitches outside, and after only one game, <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/19/manchester-city-newcastle-premier-league" title="">albeit Monday's 4-0 evisceration by Sheikh Mansour's Manchester City</a>.</p><p>Seasoned fans' despondency goes deeper than a summer of stagnation that, with a week until the transfer window closes, has produced only the striker Loïc Rémy on loan, while Arsenal's bid for Yohan Cabaye, rejected at £10m, risks branding Newcastle as a selling club.</p><p>This is reinforcing the sense that a club that made substantial all-round progress, particularly the season before last when Pardew led a replenished squad to fifth, has suddenly and bewilderingly lurched backwards. Fans' great frustration centres on the owner Ashley's decision to appoint the former Wimbledon manager, Joe Kinnear, as director of football ? a move that Ashley, characteristically, has never explained. <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jun/18/joe-kinnear-newcastle-united-interview" title="">Since Kinnear's early disastrous radio interview</a>, in which among assorted howlers and flights of fancy he named Cabaye "Yohan Kebab", Kinnear has not reassured supporters he is up to so demanding a job, which is elsewhere being greatly professionalised. The best explanation appears to be that Ashley, both at his retail chain Sports Direct and at Newcastle, likes to work with people he knows and trusts and Kinnear is a long-standing acquaintance.</p><p>But Kinnear's apparently precipitated Derek Llambias's resignation as the club's managing director, a position that has not since been filled, with his responsibilities instead split between the finance director, John Irving, and the secretary, Lee Charnley.</p><p>Llambias is also a long-standing friend of Ashley but he confounded the suspicion that another member of a "Cockney mafia" would further muck up the club by proving himself shrewd and formidable. Working with the chief scout, Graham Carr, Llambias negotiated the signings of Demba Ba, Cabaye, Papiss Cissé and Davide Santon in the summer of 2011, and Hatem Ben Arfa and Cheik Tioté the season before, while reaping £35m from selling Andy Carroll to Liverpool and wresting the club's finances, and its image, under control. Last season's 16th-place finish was disappointing and Pardew, Llambias and Carr faced convincing Ashley that they could re-engineer improvement but instead the fans now fear a Cockney mafia-style mess returning.</p><p>Pardew returned a question about Kinnear's role by saying: "We have a procedure in place. Joe is directly the in-line manager for the board and Mike, the owner, so therefore I request to him what I think the team needs and he has to try to get them over the line. We have to make sure we get one or two transfers over the line before deadline."</p><p>That made the position sound rather more structured than many fans fear. "We're wondering, if Joe Kinnear was the answer, what on earth the question was," says Michael Martin, editor of the True Faith fanzine. "This feels so erratic. Newcastle United should represent something, aspire to be a great sporting institution, but it's joyless. The club feels like a bolt-on to Sports Direct and should not have been so desperate for money they put Wonga on our shirts."</p><p>With their £7m-a-year sponsorship, Wonga restored the name St James' Park to the Sports Direct Arena but Ashley's company name is still all over the stadium and training ground. He is tightening his financial hold, reducing the £140m he loaned following his takeover of a club then deep in debt. In 2011-12 Newcastle repaid Ashley £11m and a further £18m was due for repayment by 30 June this year, although the club says none has been repaid and Pardew was adamant Newcastle do not have to sell, Cabaye or anybody else, to sign reinforcements.</p><p>Such care over spending makes a keen contrast with the club's promotion of <a href="http://www.wonga.com/money/is-this-apr-expensive/" title="">Wonga's loans at that infamous APR of 5,853%</a>. Unusually for a northern city, where local authorities tend to resist criticising their Premier League clubs, Nick Forbes, leader of Newcastle city council, is forthright in condemning the Wonga sponsorship.</p><p>He points to the economic facts for Newcastle people in a recession some way from Hall's revivalist talk: joblessness of 10.5%, youth unemployment close to 25%; 30% of Newcastle children in poverty ? and 22,000 people last year seeking advice to cope with debt. "I am horrified by Wonga cynically trying to buy respectability by linking their name with Newcastle United," Forbes says. "I hate the damage this deal is going to do to people's lives, people who can least afford to get into debt. I hate this as an image for Newcastle and feel the club could play a much more positive civic role."</p><p>In the club shop at St James' Park, with its strikingly dominant position in Newcastle, there was an eager, undaunted queue to buy the new shirt, at a 30%-off £44.99 for adults, £34.99 for children. Some boys were taking last year's straight off in the shop, putting this year's on, then walking out, bearing Wonga on their chests. Twenty years since Sir John Hall propounded that vision of revival, Mike Ashley's Newcastle United are treading nervously into their first home match, while parading payday loans to "the <sup></sup>Geordie nation".</p><div class="related" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;"><ul><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/newcastleunited">Newcastle United</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/mike-ashley">Mike Ashley</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/alan-pardew">Alan Pardew</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/joe-kinnear">Joe Kinnear</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/football/transfer-window">Transfer window</a></li><li><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/wonga">Wonga</a></li></ul></div><div class="author"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/profile/davidconn">David Conn</a></div><br/><div class="terms"><a href="http://www.theguardian.com">